{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527350"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:31:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:31:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14206"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14206"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.09,0.08,0.06,0.7]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6892"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104052"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6892"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14206"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86370"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4989"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12734"},{"type":"tags","id":"12737"},{"type":"tags","id":"12754"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15748"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36138"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48450"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104052"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old Aboriginal man presents to the General Practice clinic with poorly controlled type 2 diabetes. He has recently moved to the city for work and lives alone. He reports feeling isolated and disconnected from his community. He has a medical history of hypertension and takes metformin and perindopril. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His HbA1c is 9.5% (80 mmol/mol).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the LEAST appropriate next step to improve this patient\u0027s overall health and wellbeing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Recommend a low-carbohydrate diet","Facilitate connection with local Indigenous community groups","Refer to an endocrinologist","Increase the dose of metformin","Prescribe a selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case highlights the importance of understanding the holistic nature of health in Indigenous Australian cultures, particularly the significance of connection to kin and community. The patient\u0027s recent move and feelings of isolation are likely contributing to his poor diabetes control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing a selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor\u003C/strong\u003E is the LEAST appropriate option as there is insufficient evidence in the scenario to suggest the patient has depression or anxiety requiring pharmacological treatment. While the patient reports feeling isolated, this appears to be contextual due to his move away from community rather than indicative of a mood disorder. Prescribing an antidepressant without clear indication could expose the patient to unnecessary side effects and fails to address the cultural and social determinants affecting his wellbeing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe following are all appropriate in this patients case:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitating connection with local Indigenous community groups\u003C/strong\u003E is highly appropriate. For many Indigenous Australians, health and wellbeing are intrinsically linked to connection with family, community, and Country. By helping the patient establish connections with local Indigenous groups, we can address his feelings of isolation and potentially improve his overall health outcomes, including diabetes management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing the dose of metformin\u003C/strong\u003E is an appropriate consideration for improving glycaemic control. This addresses the biological aspect of his care while other interventions can simultaneously address the psychosocial factors. Both biomedical and cultural approaches can and should be implemented concurrently for optimal care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferring to an endocrinologist\u003C/strong\u003E is reasonable given his poorly controlled diabetes despite medication. Specialist input could help optimise his diabetes management while other aspects of his care are being addressed. Again, this demonstrates how biological and social aspects of healthcare can be addressed simultaneously.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecommending a low-carbohydrate diet\u003C/strong\u003E could potentially help with diabetes management, though this would need to be culturally appropriate and consider the patient\u0027s current circumstances. Dietary advice should be provided alongside addressing his social disconnection for a comprehensive approach to care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis question emphasises the importance of cultural safety in healthcare, which involves understanding and respecting Indigenous perspectives on health and healing. By recognising the significance of connection to kin and community in Indigenous health, healthcare providers can offer more holistic and culturally appropriate care, potentially leading to better health outcomes. Importantly, addressing both biomedical aspects (medication, diet, specialist referral) and cultural/social determinants of health should occur simultaneously rather than choosing one approach over another.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Connection to kin and Country is a fundamental aspect of Indigenous Australian health and wellbeing.","Cultural safety in healthcare involves understanding and respecting Indigenous perspectives on health and healing.","Facilitating connection to family and community can significantly improve health outcomes for Indigenous patients."],"references":["Verbunt, E., Luke, J., Paradies, Y. et al. Cultural determinants of health for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people \u2013 a narrative overview of reviews. Int J Equity Health 20, 181 (2021). https://doi.org/10.1186/s12939-021-01514-2"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86370"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14206"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86370"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-29T10:16:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-21T09:58:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6892"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104052"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"98","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/98"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Hypertension","synonyms":["Primary hypertension"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-20T08:10:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-24T20:22:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1804"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude83","name":"Indigenous Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2022-12-15T23:23:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2022-12-15T23:23:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"3505","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3505"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Type 2 diabetes mellitus","synonyms":["T2DM"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-09-23T04:54:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-23T04: